Create the cluster
kind create cluster --name mycluster --config kind-config.yaml


Verify nodes
kubectl get nodes


MetalLB installation:
Install MetalLB

kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/metallb/metallb/main/config/manifests/metallb-native.yaml


Wait for the pods:
kubectl get pods -n metallb-system


Step 4: Configure an IP address pool

You need to assign a local IP range that does not conflict with your home network.

For kind, the Docker network is usually 172.18.0.0/16.

Find it:

docker network inspect kind | grep Subnet

You will see something like:

"Subnet": "172.18.0.0/16"

Pick a range inside it, e.g., 172.18.255.200–250.

Create a config file:

# metallb-config.yaml
apiVersion: metallb.io/v1beta1
kind: IPAddressPool
metadata:
  name: default
  namespace: metallb-system
spec:
  addresses:
    - 172.18.255.200-172.18.255.250

---
apiVersion: metallb.io/v1beta1
kind: L2Advertisement
metadata:
  name: l2adv
  namespace: metallb-system


kubectl apply -f metallb-config.yaml


MetalLB is now working on your Ubuntu laptop

You can test by creating a LoadBalancer service:

kubectl expose deployment nginx --port=80 --type=LoadBalancer


Get the external IP:

kubectl get svc nginx

It will show something like:

EXTERNAL-IP: 172.18.255.200


Open it in your browser:
http://172.18.255.200




